(27, 30, 'd', 'en_us', '07.02.07.01', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/01-EnterCrdMemo.html', 'Vendor Credit Memo.Entering', 'Entering Vendor Credit Memo', 'Entering Vendor Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Vendor Credit Memos\r Credit Memos are used to enter sales to a vendor. Once a credit memo has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or credit memos can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Credit Memos do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load.\r   Enter the Vendor ID and click on the open icon right of the Vendor ID window. The vendor popup window will appear. Select the vendor from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Credit Memo form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Vendor ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find vendors.\r     \r     Vendor records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this credit memo.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Vendors can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the credit memo Post Date and expected Ship Date. Popup calendars will help with the selection.\r    Credit Memo Number - Enter the credit memo number. If left blank, the next credit memo number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the vendors purchase order number, store id and sales representative. The default accounts receivable account is loaded and can be changed. The vendor payment terms are loaded when a vendor is selected from the vendor popup. If a new vendor is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this credit memo and press Save to enter the terms into the credit memo form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the credit memo. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the credit memo form. Enter the quantity requested.\r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the credit memo. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the credit memo will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a new vendor \r Updating vendor information\r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Checking vendor balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r Credit Memos\r Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r   Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r Receiving a credit memo\r Reports\r Printing a credit memo'),
(28, 30, 'd', 'en_us', '07.02.07.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/02-EditCrdMemo.html', 'Vendor Credit Memo.Editing', 'Editing a Vendor Credit Memo', 'Editing a Vendor Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Vendor Credit Memo\r Editing an invoice can be performed at any time.\r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Credit Memos for the current period. Select the credit memo to be edited and the credit memo form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired credit memo. \r   \r   Enter any changes, as needed, to the credit memo. If any line items from the credit memo have been shipped, that particular line item cannot be deleted or the SKU changed.\r   Press the Save button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an credit memo is edited, the journal entry is re-posted in the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will  affect the income statement and balance sheet since a invoice represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Vendors\r Entering a new vendor \r Updating vendor information\r Setting vendor payment terms and credit limits \r Checking vendor balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r   Shipping an invoice\r Credit Memos \r Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r    Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)'),
(29, 30, 'd', 'en_us', '07.02.07.03', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/03-DeleteCrdMemo.html', 'Vendor Credit Memo.Deleting', 'Deleting a Vendor Credit Memo', 'Deleting a Vendor Credit Memo\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Vendor Credit Memo\r Sales orders can only be deleted if no items have been shipped from the invoice. If any items have been shipped, the corresponding invoice/sale must be removed before the invoice can be deleted. In this case, the invoice should be closed. See Closing a Credit Memo. Closing a invoice will remove all remaining ''quantity on invoice'' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Vendors Menu, select Credit Memos. The Credit Memo form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the credit memos for the current period. Select the credit memo to be deleted and the credit memo form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired credit memo. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When an credit memo is edited, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on hand values are readjusted. This action will affect the income statement and balance sheet since a credit memo represents an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Credit Memos\r  Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM) \r     Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r Closing a credit memo'),
(30, 33, '0', 'en_us', '07.02.07', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/07-CreditMemos/CreditsHome.html', 'Vendors.Credit Memos', 'Vendors - Credit Memos', 'Vendors - Credit Memos\r \r \r \r \r Vendors - Credit Memos\r  Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM) \r   Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r   Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r &nbsp;'),
(31, 33, 'd', 'en_us', '07.02.08', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/08-Status/StatusHome.html', 'Vendors.Status', 'Vendors - Status', 'Vendors - Status     Vendors - Status Status of the vendor account.'),
(32, 33, 'd', 'en_us', '07.02.09', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/09-POP/POPHome.html', 'Vendors.Point of Purchase', 'Vendors - Point of Purchase', 'Vendors - Point of Purchase     Vendors - Point of Purchase Point of purchase is the process of receiving an item and applying a payment at the time of acquisition.'),
(33, 118, '0', 'en_us', '07.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/02-Vendors/VendorHome.html', 'Vendors', 'Vendors Home', 'Vendors Home\r \r \r \r \r Vendors Home\r Vendors are your suppliers of products and services.  They are used in SmartBooks to represent people or companies that payments are made to.  This will include suppliers of your inventory items, governmental organizations for tax payments, services provided to your company (shipping companies, payroll, utilities, professional services, etc) and other expense related accounts.  Generally, vendors include anyone that you make payments to.\r SmartBooks uses a single database table to hold employee, branch, vendor and customer account information. \r Vendor account features include:\r \r   Fields for main account address along with unlimited branch billing addresses and shipping addresses.\r   Default general ledger settings for purchases\r   2 main telephone numbers, 1 fax number, email and website fields\r   Customer account number\r   Government ID (FEIN) Number\r   Discount and Payment terms specific to an account\r \r Security Settings\r Related Topics:\r Vendor Accounts\r Entering a vendor account\r   Deleting a vendor account\r   Editing a vendor account\r   Setting default payment terms \r   Adding branch and shipping addresses\r Vendor Quotes \r  Enter a vendor Request for Quote  (RFQ) \r   Edit a vendor Request for Quote (RFQ)\r   Delete a vendor Request for Quote\r   (RFQ)\r   Convert a request for quote to a Purchase Order\r Purchase Orders\r  Enter a vendor purchase order (PO) \r   Edit a vendor purchase order (PO)\r   Delete a vendor purchase order (PO)\r   Receive inventory from a purchase order (PO Manager)\r Vendor Purchases and Payments \r Receive inventory\r  Paying a bill - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.\r  Receiving inventory from a vendor \r Payments by credit card \r Vendor Credit Memos\r  Enter a vendor credit memo (VCM) \r   Edit a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r   Delete a vendor credit memo (VCM)\r Reports and Forms \r Standard vendor reports\r   Standard vendor forms\r &nbsp;'),
(34, 66, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.01', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/01-General/GeneralHome.html', 'Customers.General Information', 'Customers - General Information', 'Customers - General Information     Customers - General Information This section covers the activites realted to your customers. Accounts -  Sales Orders -  Sales Quotes -  Sales/Invoices -  Point Of Sale -  Credit Memos -  Customer  Status -'),
(35, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.01', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/01-NewAccount.html', 'Customer Accounts.Entering', 'Entering a Customer Account', 'Entering a Customer Account\r \r \r \r \r  Entering a Customer Account \r Customer accounts include any outside organization that you sell goods or services to. Generally, they are organizations that you receive payments from. \r NOTE: Customer accounts may be created at time of sale by entering the required information and checking the Add/Update button in the Sales/Invoice, Receipt or Sales Order form. In this case, an unique account ID must be entered and the account will be created using the standard terms, default Sales GL account. No User ID, Account Number, Federal ID number, or additional shipping or billing addresses will be created with the add/update feature. \r To create a new account:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;New Customer or Select the New icon form the Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r    Enter an unique Customer ID. The Customer ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this customer form all other customers. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact and Main Mailing (invoicing) Address information.  Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the default sales account. This is typically an accounts receivable general ledger account type.\r   Enter an user id assigned to this customer. \r   Enter your account number with this customer. This number can be used for sales orders, invoices to reference their account to the customer.\r    Enter the Tax or Federal ID number. generally used for tax purposes.\r    If the customer will be shipping to multiple locations, additional ship to addresses can be added in the Shipping Addresses form area. Unlimited shipping addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time.\r   Enter the payment terms you have with the customer. The defaults are preloaded but may be over-ridden on a customer by customer basis. \r   If the customer has additional remit to (invoicing) addresses, they may be added in the Billing Addresses form area. Unlimited billing addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time. \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r   Updating a customer account\r   Deleting a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Sales Orders\r Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Sales/Invoice\r Selling items from a Sales Order \r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),
(36, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/02-EditAccount.html', 'Customer Account.Editing', 'Editing a Customer Account', 'Editing a Customer Account\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Account \r To edit a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the customer to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the customer.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Deleting a customer account \r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Sales Orders\r Entering  a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),
(37, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.03', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/03-DeleteAccount.html', 'Customer Account.Deleting', 'Deleting a Customer Account', 'Deleting a Customer Account\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Account \r NOTE: Customers cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the customer to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Editing a customer account \r Sales Orders\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),
(38, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.04', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/04-PaymentTerms.html', 'Customer Accounts.Payment Terms', 'Customer Payment Terms', 'Customer Payment Terms\r \r \r \r \r Customer Payment Terms\r Customer payment terms may be set up through the configuration screen. The terms set up will be applied as the default terms for all new customer account.  Additionally, existing accounts with out terms defined (or ''Use Standard Terms'') will track the terms defined in the configuration setup definitions. Individual customer terms may also be set up for customers whose terms are different from the standard terms. Terms may also be set up for specific sales through the Sales Order/Invoice procedure. \r Setting up Default Terms \r \r   Select Company-&gt;Customer Defaults.\r   Edit the fields as necessary. The terms type defaults to the standard X% discount in Y days, Net Z days.\r   Set the default customer credit limit to use. \r \r Setting up Customer Specific Payment Terms\r \r    Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers. \r   Search for the customer whose terms you want to change and press the edit icon to reach the detailed page.\r    Under the section titled Payment Terms, check the radio button for the terms type to apply to this customer.\r   Depending on the terms type selected, the Discount, Due In, Net and date fields will be active. Fill in the fields for the terms type selected.\r   Enter the credit limit for the current customer.\r   Press the Save icon to save the changes.\r \r Setting Payment Terms for a Single Purchase\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales/Invoice (or Sales Order, Customer Quote).\r   On the form select the Open icon next to the terms field. A popup window will open with the current terms selected.\r   Change the terms as necessary and press Save to enter the new terms into the form.\r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer account\r   Editing a customer account\r Sales Orders\r  Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),
(39, 66, '0', 'en_us', '07.03.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Accounts/AccountsHome.html', 'Customers.Customer Accounts', 'Customers - Customer Accounts', 'Customers - Customer Accounts\r \r \r \r \r Customers -  Accounts\r Customer accounts contain information about your customers of your business. The procedures to setup, edit and delete customer account is similar to that for vendors within SmartBooks. \r Customer Account features:\r \r   Default global settings for sales account and terms; customizable for each individual customer \r   Unlimited billing addresses\r   Unlimited shipping addresses\r    Individual sales rep default assignment \r   Free-form notes field \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a new Customer\r   Updating customer information\r   Deleting a Customer\r Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r   Printing a sales order\r   Checking sales order status \r \r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing inventory from a sales order\r Using point of sale (POS)\r Other Customer Actions \r Checking customer balances \r   Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Receiving a payment from a customer\r   Issuing a credit memo\r &nbsp;'),
(40, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.01', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/01-NewContact.html', 'Customer Contacts.Entering', 'Entering a Customer Contact', 'Entering a Customer Contact\r \r \r \r \r  Entering a Customer Contact \r Customer contacts include any outside organization that you sell goods or services to. Generally, they are organizations that you receive payments from. \r NOTE: Customer contacts may be created at time of sale by entering the required information and checking the Add/Update button in the Sales/Invoice, Receipt or Sales Order form. In this case, an unique contact ID must be entered and the contact will be created using the standard terms, default Sales GL account. No User ID, Account Number, Federal ID number, or additional shipping or billing addresses will be created with the add/update feature. \r To create a new contact:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;New Customer or Select the New icon form the Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r    Enter an unique Customer ID. The Customer ID (or short name) is an unique field to identify this customer form all other customers. Maximum length is 20 characters.\r   Enter remaining Primary Contact  and Main Mailing (invoicing) Address information. Required fields are identified by a (*).\r   Enter the default sales account. This is typically an accounts receivable general ledger account type.\r   Enter an user id assigned to this customer. \r   Enter your account number with this customer. This number can be used for sales orders, invoices to reference their account to the customer.\r    Enter the Tax or Federal ID number. generally used for tax purposes.\r    If the customer will be shipping to multiple locations, additional ship to addresses can be added in the Shipping Addresses form area. Unlimited shipping addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time.\r   Enter the payment terms you have with the customer. The defaults are preloaded but may be over-ridden on a customer by customer basis. \r   If the customer has additional remit to (invoicing) addresses, they may be added in the Billing Addresses form area. Unlimited billing addresses may be assigned to a customer but only one may be added at a time. \r   Press the Save icon and the record will be saved and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r   Updating a customer contact\r   Deleting a customer contact\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Sales Orders\r Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Sales/Invoice\r Selling items from a Sales Order \r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),
(41, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/02-EditContact.html', 'Customer Contacts.Editing', 'Editing a Customer Contact', 'Editing a Customer Contact\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Contact \r To edit a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Edit icon next to the customer to edit. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Edit/update/change any fields for the customer.\r   Add/Delete any additional shipping or billing addresses.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes. You will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer contact \r   Deleting a customer contact \r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Sales Orders\r Entering  a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),
(42, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.03', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/03-DeleteContact.html', 'Customer Contacts.Deleting', 'Deleting a Customer Contact', 'Deleting a Customer Contact\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Contact \r NOTE: Customers cannot be deleted if they have a journal entry associated with them. \r To delete a customer record:\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers page.\r   Select the Delete icon next to the customer to delete. A search box has been provided to quickly locate the customer.\r   Confirm the deletion and you will be returned to the Maintain Customers page. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer contact \r   Editing a customer contact \r Sales Orders\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),
(43, 39, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02.04', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/04-PaymentTerms.html', 'Customer Accounts.Payment Terms', 'Customer Payment Terms', 'Customer Payment Terms\r \r \r \r \r Customer Payment Terms\r Customer payment terms may be set up through the configuration screen. The terms set up will be applied as the default terms for all new customer contacts. Additionally, existing contacts with out terms defined (or ''Use Standard Terms'') will track the terms defined in the configuration setup definitions. Individual customer terms may also be set up for customers whose terms are different from the standard terms. Terms may also be set up for specific sales through the Sales Order/Invoice procedure. \r Setting up Default Terms \r \r   Select Company-&gt;Customer Defaults.\r   Edit the fields as necessary. The terms type defaults to the standard X% discount in Y days, Net Z days.\r   Set the default customer credit limit to use. \r \r Setting up Customer Specific Payment Terms\r \r    Select Customers-&gt;Maintain Customers. \r   Search for the customer whose terms you want to change and press the edit icon to reach the detailed page.\r    Under the section titled Payment Terms, check the radio button for the terms type to apply to this customer.\r   Depending on the terms type selected, the Discount, Due In, Net and date fields will be active. Fill in the fields for the terms type selected.\r   Enter the credit limit for the current customer.\r   Press the Save icon to save the changes.\r \r Setting Payment Terms for a Single Purchase\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales/Invoice (or Sales Order, Customer Quote).\r   On the form select the Open icon next to the terms field. A popup window will open with the current terms selected.\r   Change the terms as necessary and press Save to enter the new terms into the form.\r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r  Adding a new customer contact\r   Editing a customer contact\r Sales Orders\r  Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Reports and Forms \r Checking customer balances\r &nbsp;'),
(44, 66, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/02-Contacts/ContactsHome.html', 'Customers.Customer Contacts', 'Customers - Customer Contacts', 'Customers - Customer Contacts\r \r \r \r \r Customers -  Contacts\r Customer contacts contain information about your customers of your business. The procedures to setup, edit and delete customer contacts is similar to that for vendors within SmartBooks. \r Customer Account features:\r \r   Default global settings for sales account and terms; customizable for each individual customer \r   Unlimited billing addresses\r   Unlimited shipping addresses\r    Individaul sales rep default assignment \r   Freee-form notes field \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a new Customer\r   Updating customer information\r   Deleting a Customer\r Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r   Printing a sales order\r   Checking sales order status \r \r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing inventory from a sales order\r \r Point of Sale (POS)\r \r Other Customer Actions \r Checking customer balances \r   Generating a request for quote (RFQ) \r   Receiving a payment from a customer\r   Issuing a credit memo\r &nbsp;'),
(45, 50, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.03.01', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/01-EnterSO.html', 'Sales Orders.Entering', 'Entering Customer Sales Orders', 'Entering Customer Sales Orders\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Customer Sales Orders\r Sales orders are used to enter sales to a customer. Once a sales order has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or invoices can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Sales orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load.\r   Enter the Customer ID and click on the open icon right of the Customer ID window. The customer popup window will appear. Select the customer from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the Sales Order form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Customer ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find customers.\r     \r     Customer records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this sales order.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the sales order Post Date and expected Ship Date. Popup calendars will help with the selection.\r    Sales Order Number - Enter the sales order number. If left blank, the next sales order number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the customers purchase order number, store id and sales representative. The default accounts receivable account is loaded and can be changed. The customer payment terms are loaded when a customer is selected from the customer popup. If a new customer is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this sales order and press Save to enter the terms into the sales order form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the sales order. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the sales order form. Enter the quantity requested.\r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the sales order. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the Purchase Order number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the sales order will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers Accounts\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Updating a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r  Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Shipping Estimator\r Setting up the shipping estimator\r Shipping a sales order\r Sales Orders\r Deleting a sales order\r  Closing a sales order\r Printing a sales order\r Printing a pick list/packing list\r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing a sales order'),
(46, 50, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.03.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/02-EditSO.html', 'Customer Sales Orders.Editing', 'Editing a Customer Sales Order', 'Editing a Customer Sales Order\r \r \r \r \r Editing a Customer Sales Order\r Sales  orders can only be edited if no items have been received from the sales order. If any items have been received, the corresponding sales/receipt must be removed before the sales order can be edited. In this case, the sales order should be closed. See Closing a Sales Order. Closing a sales order will remove all remaining ''quantity on  order'' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the sales orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be edited and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired sales order. \r   \r   Make any necessary changes. Item rows may not be changed if some or all have been received.\r   Press the Save button to save the changes.\r \r When a sales order is saves, the journal entry is re-posted to the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a sales order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sales (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r Entering a new customer \r     Editing a customer contact \r     Deleting a customer contact \r     Setting customer payment\r     Payment terms and credit limits \r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r &nbsp;'),
(47, 50, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.03.03', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/03-DeleteSO.html', 'Sales Orders.Deleting', 'Deleting a Customer Sales Order', 'Deleting a Customer Sales Order\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Sales Order\r Sales orders can only be deleted if no items have been shipped from the sales order. If any items have been shipped, the corresponding invoice/sale must be removed before the sales order can be deleted. In this case, the sales order should be closed. See Closing a Sales Order. Closing a sales order will remove all remaining ''quantity on sales order'' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the sales order for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired purchase order. \r     \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a Sales Order is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on sales order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a sales order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sale (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Sales Orders\r Entering  a sales order\r     Closing a sales order'),
(48, 50, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.03.04', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/04-SOManager.html', 'Sales Orders.SO Manager', 'Sales Order Manager', 'Sales Order Manager\r \r \r \r Sales Order Manager\r The sales order manager is a powerful tool to manage your companies sales orders. From this function, you can  enter and review expected shipment dates, print copies of the sales order, or edit the sales order. The sales order manager default to the current period but a search field and period selection pull down are provided to help locate SOs anywhere in the system.\r Sales Order Manager Features:\r \r   Easily view sales orders and determine open/closed status and expected shipment dates \r   Powerful search capabilities to find or filter results\r   Ability to print SOs without opening them up or re-posting\r   Ability to set expected shipment dates so you know when shipments are expected, helps manage inventory\r   Ability to open for edit the sales order and review additional details\r   Ability to invoice a sales order \r \r Viewing a Sales Order\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager\r   Locate the sales order to view and press the icon labeled Edit.\r   The Sales Order screen will load and the form will be filled in with the information of the selected SO.\r   From here, the sales order may be edited, deleted, closed or reviewed.\r \r Printing a Sales Order\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager\r   Locate the sales order to print and press the icon labeled Print.\r   The reportwriter form display screen will appear listing the available forms to print.\r   Select the form to print, the delivery method, and press the PDF icon to generate the form. \r \r Invoicing a Sales Order\r \r   Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager \r   Locate the sales order to invoice and press the button labeled Invoice.\r   The Sales/Invoice screen will load and the remaining items from the selected SO will be shown.\r   Enter in the quantities to ship for each line item.\r    Make any other changes as necessary; such as the customers purchase order number shipment details, etc.\r   Press the Save icon to save the invoice or the receipt icon to receive payment form the customer.\r \r Changing Delivery Dates for a Sales Order\r When a sales order is placed, the expected shipment date is set to the post date. The estimated shipment dates may be modified here to reflect the current estimated shipment dates for each line item on the SO. the shipment dates field is useful to identify when items are expected for filling back-orders and notifications of expected arrivals of inventory items.\r \r    Select Customers-&gt;Sales Order Manager \r   Locate the sales order to adjust or view the expected shipment dates and press the button labeled ''Delivery Dates''.\r   A popup will appear listing each line item from the SO, the quantity ordered and the description. The currently expected shipment date will also be displayed.\r   If necessary, enter a new shipment date for each item on the SO. A popup calendar is provided to help locate dates. If no change is necessary, leave the date field blank to retain the current shipment date. \r   After updating all affected shipment dates, press the Save icon the save the charges and return to the Sales Order Manager window. \r \r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r Adding a new customer account \r    Updating a customer account\r    Deleting a customer account\r   Setting customer payment terms and credit limits\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r     Editing a sales order\r     Deleting a sales order\r     Closing a sales order\r Reports and Forms \r Open sales order report'),
(49, 50, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.03.05', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/05-CloseSO.html', 'Sales Orders.CLosing', 'Closing a Customer Sales Order', 'Closing a Customer Sales Order\r \r \r \r \r Closing a Customer Sales Order\r Sales  orders can  be closed for several reasons. They may be closed directly from the Edit SO screen by selecting the close button. Closed SOs will not affect the inventory levels or appear in any inventory stock level calculations. SOs may also be closed by SmartBooks if all the items have been shipped through the Sales/invoice screen. Closing a sales order will remove all remaining ''quantity on  sales order'' quantities from inventory identified in the sales order being closed that have not been shipped. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Sales Orders. The Sales Order form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the sales orders for the current period. Select the sales order to be closed and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired sales order. \r   \r   Check the Close selection box.\r   Press the Save button.\r \r When a sales order is closed, the  quantity on  sales order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a sales order represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual sales (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r     Editing a sales order\r     Deleting a sales order\r Checking sales order status (Sales Order Manager) \r &nbsp;'),
(50, 66, '0', 'en_us', '07.03.03', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/03-SalesOrders/SOHome.html', 'Overview.Sales Orders', 'Entering Customer Sales Orders', 'Entering Customer Sales Orders\r \r \r \r \r  Customer Sales Orders\r Sales orders are used to enter sales to a customer. Once a sales order has been entered several events may then occur. Inventory items can be ordered (Purchase Orders), items shipped or drop-shipped, pick slips, packing slips or invoices can be generated for some or all of the items in the order as they become available in your inventory. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls inventory sales. Sales orders do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to fulfill sales. \r Partial shipments are possible from a single sales order.\r NOTE: Sales orders are not required if you operate in a point-of-sale type sales system. In this case entering the sales directly as sales/invoice or point-of-sale is all that is required. \r Related Topics\r Customer Accounts\r  Adding a new customer account \r   Updating a customer account\r   Setting up a customer credit limit\r  Checking customer balances \r \r Sales Orders\r Entering a sales order\r   Deleting a sales order\r   Closing a sales order\r Printing a pick list/packing list\r Sales/Invoicing\r Invoicing a sales order\r Shipping\r Shipping a sales order'),
(51, 54, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.04.01', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/01-EnterQuote.html', 'Customer Request for Quote.Entering', 'Entering Customer Request for Quote', 'Entering Customer Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Entering Customer Request for Quote\r Request for Quote are used to enter purchase from a customer. Reports can be generated to list the inventory shortfalls and inventory purchases. Each inventory item has a minimum balance field that can be used to help identify when inventory needs to be ordered. Request for Quotes do not affect your financial situation, income statement or balance sheet. they merely act as a placeholder to determine inventory stock levels needed to add or replace inventory stock levels. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load.\r   Enter the Customer ID and click on the open icon right of the Customer ID window. The customer popup window will appear. Select the customer from the list and the information will be pre-loaded into the request for quote form.\r     \r     NOTE: The Customer ID text box also acts as a search box to quickly find customers.\r     \r     Customer records consist of a main address, billing addresses and shipping addresses. Select the billing address and shipping address from the pull down menus. New addresses may be added to either the shipping or billing address if they cannot be found from either of the menus. Selecting the add/update button will update the database whereas leaving it unchecked will just retain the address for this request for quote.\r     Drop Ship - If this is a drop ship, select the Drop Ship box and the drop ship search box will appear. Customers can be searched and their shipping information will be entered into the drop down or the shipping address may be entered directly into the address fields. \r   Enter the request for quote Post Date and expected Receipt Date. Popup calendars are provided to help with the selection.\r    request for quote Number - Enter the request for quote number. If left blank, the next sequential request for quote number will be automatically generated by the system.\r    Enter the your purchase reference   number, store id and purchase representative. The default accounts payable account is loaded and can be changed. The customer payment terms are loaded when a customer is selected from the customer popup. If a new customer is entered, the default payment terms are loaded. To change the payment terms, click on the icon next to the terms text field and the terms popup will be displayed. Select the terms for this request for quote and press Save to enter the terms into the request for quote form.\r   Enter the inventory items for the request for quote. The form defaults with a single inventory line but more may be added by pressing the Add button located in the lower left area of the request for quote form. Enter the quantity requested. The item cost value assigned to the sku will be placed in the price field and the line total will be calculated. \r     \r     NOTE: The inventory SKU field also acts as a search field for the inventory popup. To quickly find an inventory item, enter part of the item sku or description and press the icon next to the SKU. The SKU, description and pricing fields will be filled in. \r     \r   Enter the inventory SKU, description and price (or retrieve from the inventory popup) for the line item. Enter more line items as necessary. \r   Enter the shipping charges (or use the shipping estimator to calculate freight charges).\r   Select  the tax authority, the tax will be automatically calculated.\r   Save or Print the request for quote. Error checking will be performed and any errors will be indicated either in a popup for errors before the form is submitted or at the top of the reloaded page (for errors during  processing). If the request for quote number field was left blank, a number will be assigned by the system. If the Print button was selected, the request for quote will be posted first followed by a popup window displaying the possible forms to print, select the form to print and press the Print button. \r \r Related Topics\r Customers\r Entering a customer account\r    Editing a customer account\r    Setting up a customer credit limit\r Checking customer balances \r Tax Authorities \r Setting up tax authorities\r    Setting up tax rates\r Request for Quotes\r  Deleting a request for quote \r Closing a request for quote\r Printing a request for quote'),
(52, 54, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.04.02', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/02-EditQuote.html', 'Customer Request for Quote.Deleting', 'Deleting a Customer Request for Quote', 'Deleting a Customer Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Editing a Customer Request for Quote\r Customer sales  quotes can only be deleted if no items have been received from the request for quote. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the request for quote can be deleted. In this case, the request for quote should be closed. See Closing a request for quote. Closing a request for quote will remove all remaining ''quantity on  order'' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Request for Quotes for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired request for quote. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a request for quote is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a request for quote represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Request for Quotes\r  Enter a customer request for quote \r Delete a customer request for quote \r Closing a request for quote\r &nbsp;'),
(53, 54, 'd', 'en_us', '07.03.04.03', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/03-DeleteQuote.html', 'Customer Request for Quote.Deleting', 'Deleting a Customer Request for Quote', 'Deleting a Customer Request for Quote\r \r \r \r \r  Deleting a Customer Request for Quote\r Purchase  quotes can only be deleted if no items have been received from the request for quote. If any items have been received, the corresponding purchase/receipt must be removed before the request for quote can be deleted. In this case, the request for quote should be closed. See Closing a request for quote. Closing a request for quote will remove all remaining ''quantity on  order'' quantities from inventory. \r \r   From the Customers Menu, select Request for Quote. The request for quote form will load. \r   Press the Open button and a popup will appear listing the Request for Quotes for the current period. Select the sales order to be deleted and the sales order form will be filled in. \r     \r     NOTE: Use the period pull down and search box to facilitate locating the desired request for quote. \r   \r   Press the Delete button and confirm the action on the confirmation popup.\r \r When a request for quote is deleted, the journal entry is removed from the database and the quantity on  order values are readjusted. This action will not affect the income statement or balance sheet since a request for quote represents an allocation of inventory and not an actual purchase (monetary transaction).\r Related Topics\r Request for Quotes\r  Enter a customer request for quote \r Edit a customer request for quote \r Closing a request for quote\r &nbsp;'),
(54, 66, '0', 'en_us', '07.03.04', 'modules/contacts/language/en_us/manual/03-Customers/04-Quotes/QuotesHome.html', 'Customers.Quotes', 'Customers - Quotes', 'Customers - Quotes\r \r \r Customers - Quotes\r Customer Request for Quotes\r  Enter a customer request for quote \r Edit a customer request for quote \r Delete a customer request for quote \r &nbsp;');
