(87, 88, 'd', 'en_us', '07.04.04.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/04-Inventory/04-Tabs/02-TabsDelete.html', 'Inventory.Tabs - Delete', 'Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Delete)', 'Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Delete)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Tabs (Category) (Delete)\r WARNING: Deleting a tab will also delete all inventory fields that are part of that tab. To keep the fields, edit each inventory field and reassign them to a valid tab before deleting.\r Deleting an Inventory tab (category)\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Field Tabs.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Edit the inventory tab fields. \r   Press the Delete button to delete and a confirmation will appear.\r   Press the Delete button on the confirmation to delete the tab.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory tab (category) \r     Inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),
(88, 92, '0', 'en_us', '07.04.04', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/04-Inventory/04-Tabs/TabsHome.html', 'Inventory.Tabs', 'Inventory - Tabs (Categories)', 'Inventory - Tabs (Categories)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Tabs (Categories)\r SmartBooks has a built in feature to expand inventory attributes (fields) to allow for further refinement of your inventory items.  To help organize these expanded fields, added inventory fields are organized into categories. These categories become the tab headings when maintaining your inventory items. The mandatory inventory fields are, by default, put into the ''System'' tab. If the inventory type is an assembly, a second tab name ''Bill of Materials'' is also added. At least one tab must be added before inventory fields can be entered.\r Adding an Inventory Tab (Category)\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Field Tabs.\r   Press the New button.\r   Enter a short name for the inventory tab, 10 characters or less, no spaces.\r   Enter the sort position. This will determine the display order of the tabs when maintaining inventory items.\r   Enter a tab description. This field will show up below the tab to describe the contents of the tab. \r   Press Insert to add the new tab. \r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Editing an inventory tab (category)\r     Deleting an inventory tab (category)\r     Add inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),
(89, 91, 'd', 'en_us', '07.04.05.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/04-Inventory/05-Fields/01-FieldsEdit.html', 'Inventory.Custom Fields - Edit', 'Inventory - Custom Fields (Edit)', 'Inventory - Custom Fields (Edit)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Custom Fields (Edit)\r Editing a Custom Inventory Field \r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Fields.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Edit the custom inventory fields. \r   Press Update to save your changes.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r     Adding an inventory field\r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),
(90, 91, 'd', 'en_us', '07.04.05.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/04-Inventory/05-Fields/02-FieldsDelete.html', 'Inventory.Custom Fields - Delete', 'Inventory - Custom Fields (Delete)', 'Inventory - Custom Fields (Delete)\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Custom Fields (Delete)\r WARNING: Deleting a inventory custom field will delete all inventory information stored in the targeted field. This action is not reversible. \r Deleting an Inventory Custom Field\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Fields.\r   Click anywhere on the row to highlight.\r   Press the Edit button. \r   Press the Delete button to delete and a confirmation will appear.\r   Press the Delete button on the confirmation to delete the custom field.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r     Inventory fields\r     Editing an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),
(91, 92, '0', 'en_us', '07.04.05', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/04-Inventory/05-Fields/FieldsHome.html', 'Inventory.Custom Fields', 'Inventory - Custom Fields', 'Inventory - Custom Fields\r \r \r \r \r Inventory - Custom Fields\r SmartBooks has a built in feature to expand inventory fields (attributes) to allow for further refinement of your inventory items. To help organize these expanded fields, added inventory fields are organized into categories. These categories become the tab headings when maintaining your inventory items. The mandatory inventory fields are, by default, put into the ''System'' category (tab). If the inventory type is an assembly, a second tab name ''Bill of Materials'' is also added. At least one category must be added before inventory fields can be entered. As many fields can be added to a category as are needed. \r Adding an Inventory Field\r \r   From the main menu select Inventory-&gt;Setup Inventory Fields.\r   Press the New button.\r   Enter a short name for the inventory field name, 10 characters or less, no spaces. This field must be compatible with the database naming convention. (mysql, etc.) \r   Enter a description. This is the field that will generally be used when maintaining inventory.\r   Select the category to place this field into. This will determine what tab heading the field will appear when inventory items are edited.\r   Enter the field type and properties. On some fields, default properties may be entered to pre-define the field when a new item is entered. \r   Press New to add the new inventory field.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Delete inventory items\r     Inventory adjustments\r     Inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r     Editing an inventory field \r     Deleting an inventory field\r Import/Export\r Importing Inventory\r   Exporting inventory\r &nbsp;'),
(92, 118, '0', 'en_us', '07.04', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/04-Inventory/InventoryHome.html', 'Inventory', 'Inventory Home', 'Inventory Home\r \r \r \r \r Inventory\r SmartBooks uses inventory to represent all items, activities, and services your company offers to its customers. \r Inventory types include:\r Stock - Represents items that are stocked by your company. This includes items that are purchased and re-sold by your company without any value-added provided by your company. Retail type companies typically use stock type items. Stock item movement and cost is tracked in the general ledger. \r Master-Stock - Master-stock items are items that contain attributes associated with the item. For example, a shirt item would have the attributes size and color associated with each item. Phreebooks will assign a unique item id to each variation to track inventory activity of each size/color item but retain the link to the master stock item for reporting activity. Master-stock item movement and cost is tracked in the general ledger. \r Serialized - Serialized items are items that are assembled and sold  by an unique serial number. Serialized item movement and cost are tracked in the general ledger. \r Assemblies - Item assemblies consist of one or more inventory items grouped together and sold as an individual item. This inventory type can also be used to group items sold as packages. Assembly item movement and cost is tracked in the general ledger. \r Non-stock - Non-stock items are physical items whose costs are not tracked in the general ledger. They may include supplies, packaging material, assembly materials, etc. \r Labor - Labor items are associated with employee chargeable time. Labor may be applied to either internal work order activities as well as labor charges to customer for services performed. Labor is typically charged by a time unit (hourly, daily, etc).\r Service - Service items are items that typically represent a fixed charged for a service. For example, a packaging charge or handling would be a service. Service costs are tracked in the general ledger. \r Charge - A charge item would be a fixed price charge for materials and/or services. Shop supplies and disposal fees would be examples of charges. Charge item costs are tracked in the general ledger. \r Activity - \r Description - This is a text only item used to communicate information. No cost or activity is tracked in the general ledger. The description item would be typically used for standard statements included with purchase orders, sales orders, etc. \r Inventory Categories\r Phreebooks uses system and company categories to organize inventory characteristics. A default tab for system required fields cannot be edited or deleted. A second tab will be displayed for assembly type inventory items. Additional tabs may be added by the company to help further define the characteristics of their inventory items. For example, additional tabs may be added to include product dimensions, shipping properties, application descriptions, etc. \r Inventory Fields\r SmartBooks allows additional fields to be entered to the inventory database table. This allows customized inventory characteristics to be added to fit your companies needs. Inventory field types include text, HTML, hyperlinks, image paths, inventory links, integers and floating point numbers, dates and times, drop-down menus radio buttons and checkboxes. Refer to the section on inventory fields for more information. \r Related Topics\r User and Security Settings\r Setting user access security\r Inventory Activities \r  Adding inventory items\r     Editing inventory items\r     Copying inventory items\r     Delete inventory items\r     Entering an inventory assembly\r Inventory Categories\r  Add inventory field tabs (categories)\r     Editing an inventory field tab (category) \r     Deleting an inventory field tab (category)\r Inventory Fields \r Adding an inventory field\r    Editing and inventory field\r    Deleting an inventory field\r  General Ledger\r Setting up default inventory accounts \r   Adding, editing and deleting general ledger accounts \r Importing/Exporting\r Building an import/export map\r   Importing/Exporting data\r Reports\r &nbsp;'),
(93, 95, 'd', 'en_us', '07.05.01.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/01-Payments/01-SinglePayments.html', 'Banking.Single Payments', 'Banking - Single Payments', 'Banking - Single Payments\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Single Payments\r This procedure covers payments via check, eft, or other non-paper method to a single vendor. This method is best used when payment is desired to a single vendor as it allows for easier selection of the vendor of interest. Payments Ref Numbers cannot be duplicated in the system. \r To pay a bill to a single vendor - writing a check \r \r   From the menu click on Banking -&gt; Pay Bills.\r   Enter part of the vendor name to search for and press the open folder icon next to the vendor id field.\r   A popup will be displayed showing the vendors that match the entered search criteria. NOTE: Only the vendors that have an outstanding bill to be paid will be displayed. If the vendor is not listed, make sure there is an open invoice entered into SmartBooks to pay.\r   Click anywhere on the vendor name to fill in the Payments form and close the popup.\r   All outstanding invoices from this vendor will be displayed, including any open vendor credit memos. Click on the Pay checkbox next to all the invoices you wish to pay. If the vendor payment terms have been set, any early payment discounts will be calculated. They may also be entered manually (note that the balance is calculated automatically if a discount is entered).\r   Enter the Payment Ref #, this is usually the check number to be printed.\r    Enter the check date, Reference, and account information as necessary. \r   Press the Print icon to generate the form. The forms of type banking:checks will be displayed. Check the radio button of the form to print, select the delivery method and press the PDF icon. \r   Print to the pre-printed checks on the printer.\r \r The Payment Ref Num will be automatically incremented.\r To pay a bill via EFT, credit card, and other non-check methods \r \r   Follow the procedure above, except enter an unique Payment Ref that identifies the payment. Select the correct account and post the payment by clicking the Save icon. To pay by credit card, select a short term liability account to post the payment to. \r \r NOTE: After paying with this method, the Payment Ref Num will auto-increment, probably to something non-desirable. It will need to be re-entered (back to the next check num) when the next run of bills are paid by checks to the next check number.\r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Creating Inventory Items\r     Receiving Inventory \r Banking\r  Paying Bills - Single Payment\r     Paying Bills - Bulk Payment\r   Paying Bills with credit cards \r   Reconciling cash accounts \r Reports \r Bank Checks\r &nbsp;'),
(94, 95, 'd', 'en_us', '07.05.01.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/01-Payments/02-BulkPayments.html', 'Banking.Bulk Payments', 'Banking - Bulk Payments', 'Banking - Bulk Payments\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Bulk Payments\r This procedure covers payments via check, eft, or other non-paper method to one or more vendors. This method is preferred for paying vendor invoices to multiple vendors in a single operation. Payments Ref Numbers cannot be duplicated in the system but this procedure automatically increments the Payment Ref Numbers as each payment is generated. \r To pay a bill to multiple vendors - writing a checks \r \r   From the menu click on Banking -&gt; Select for Payment. A list of invoices that are due today will be displayed. Grayed out invoices may be shown and are an indication of invoices that are due but do not have an invoice number assigned to them.\r   Select a date form the Invoices Due By and Discounts Lost By calendar selections and press the Search icon. \r   A new list of invoices that are due (or discounts lost) will be displayed. Select all of the invoice to pay in this batch by checking the Pay checkboxes next tot he invoices to pay or press the Pay All icon to have SmartBooks check all the boxes for you. Uncheck any invoices you don''t want to pay. Discounts are automatically calculated and the balance of the cash account is calculated. \r   Enter the First Check Number, this is  the first check number to be printed. SmartBooks will automatically increment the check number as the check for each vendor is generated. \r    Enter the check date,  and gl account information as necessary. \r   Press the Print icon to generate the form. The forms of type banking:checks will be displayed. Check the radio button of the form to print, select the delivery method and press the PDF icon. \r   SmartBooks generates one check page for each vendor, combing all invoices from the same vendor into a single check. Print to the pre-printed checks on the printer (make sure the sequence is correct).\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Creating Inventory Items\r     Receiving Inventory \r Banking\r  Paying Bills - Single Payment\r     Paying Bills - Bulk Payment\r   Paying Bills with credit cards \r   Reconciling cash accounts \r Reports \r Bank Checks\r &nbsp;'),
(95, 100, '0', 'en_us', '07.05.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/01-Payments/PaymentsHome.html', 'Banking.Payments', 'Banking - Payments', 'Banking - Payments\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Payments\r Bill Payments by Check - There are two ways to pay bills, individually or in bulk:\r  Paying Bills - Single Payment\r     Paying Bills - Bulk Payment\r &nbsp;'),
(96, 97, 'd', 'en_us', '07.05.02.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/02-Receipts/01-SingleReceipts.html', 'Banking.Customer Receipts', 'Banking - Customer Receipts', 'Banking - Customer Receipts\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Customer Receipts\r This procedure covers payments via check, eft, or other  method from a single customer. Receipt Ref Numbers are automatically generated by the system (but can be over-ridden) to group deposits together. Deposit reference numbers can be duplicated in the system. \r Receiving Payment from a Customer\r \r   Select Banking-&gt;Customer Receipts .\r    Enter the Customer ID or press the open icon next to the Customer ID field. A popup will appear only displaying the customers with outstanding invoices. \r    Select the customer that you received a payment from. The popup window will close and fill in the list of outstanding invoices on the receipts form.\r   Check the Pay box of the invoices you receive money from. Adjust the discount as necessary. \r   Use the pre-selected deposit reference number of enter a reference number in the Deposit  ID field.\r   Enter the date of the deposit (default is today).\r   Change the cash and discount accounts if necessary.\r   Select the Deposit method from the pull down menu. Payment receipt methods are determined by the payment modules installed. Every payment module has their own set of fields to enter. Fill in any necessary payment information.\r   Either Save or Print the payment. Saving is typically used for payments received where no receipt is necessary whereas printing is typically used for when a receipt is necessary (such as POS). The payment will be posted to the general ledger. \r \r To pay a bill via EFT, credit card, and other non-check methods \r \r   Follow the procedure above, except enter an unique Payment Ref that identifies the payment. Select the correct account and post the payment by clicking the Save icon.\r \r Related Topics\r Inventory\r Creating Inventory Items\r     Receiving Inventory \r Banking\r  \r Reconciling cash accounts \r Viewing the balance of a cash account\r \r Reports \r Bank Checks\r   Deposit Slips \r &nbsp;'),
(97, 100, '0', 'en_us', '07.05.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/02-Receipts/ReceiptsHome.html', 'Banking.Receipts', 'Banking - Receipts', 'Banking - Receipts\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Receipts\r When a customer submits a payment for an outstanding invoice, the banking receipts function is used. \r Receiving Payment from a Customer\r \r   Select Banking-&gt;Customer Receipts .\r    Enter the Customer ID or press the open icon next to the Customer ID field. A popup will appear only displaying the customers with outstanding invoices. \r    Select the customer that you received a payment from. The popup window will close and fill in the list of outstanding invoices on the Pay Bills form.\r   Check the Pay box of the invoices you wish to pay. Adjust the discount as necessary. \r   Enter a Reference Number in the Reference field.\r   Enter the check number in the Deposit Ticket ID field.\r   Enter the date of the check (default is today).\r   Change the cash and discount accounts if necessary.\r   Select the Payment Method from the pull down menu. Fill in any necessary payment information.\r   Either Save or Print the payment. Saving is typically used for payments received where no receipt is necessary whereas printing is typically used for when a receipt is necessary (such as POS). The payment will be posted to the general ledger. \r \r Related Topics\r Voiding a Receipt \r   Editing a Receipt \r   Deleting a Receipt \r &nbsp;'),
(98, 100, 'd', 'en_us', '07.05.03', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/03-BankRegister/RegisterHome.html', 'Banking.Cash Register', 'Banking - Cash Register', 'Banking - Cash Register\r \r \r \r \r Banking - Cash Register \r SmartBooks provides a view of the current status of your cash accounts. The register shows all deposits and withdrawals for a given accounting period, including future posted transactions.\r To View Your Cash Account\r \r   Select Banking -&gt; Bank Account Register.\r   The screen will display a beginning balance for the period and all transactions that were posted for the period. \r   To change cash accounts, select a new account from the GL Account pull down menu. \r \r Related Topics\r Reports\r Printing Deposit Slips \r Printing Bank Checks'),
(99, 100, 'd', 'en_us', '07.05.04', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/04-Reconcilliation/ReconcilliationHome.html', 'Banking.Account Reconciliation', 'Banking - Account Reconciliation', 'Banking - Account Reconciliation     Banking - Account Reconciliation Account reconciliation balances the smartbooks cash account with your financial institution.  Account Reconciliation    Open the account reconciliation screen by selecting Banking-&gt;Account Reconciliation.   Select the cash account to reconcile.   enter the ending balance in the Statement Ending Balance&nbsp;box. The unreconciled amount will appear in the Unreconciled Difference box.    Check the box next to the item as cleared that appear on you financial institutions statement.    After checking all cleared items, the Unreconciled difference should be zero. If not recheck you checked boxes with your statement and correct any errors.   Press the Save icon to save your changes.'),
(100, 118, '0', 'en_us', '07.05', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/05-Banking/BankingHome.html', 'Banking', 'Banking Home', 'Banking Home     Banking Phreebooks tracks customer payments and payments to vendors.  The following services are available in SmartBooks: Customer Receipts - Checks, credit cards, and EFTs from your customers. Vendor Payments - Checks, EFTs to you suppliers and service providers.   Bank Account Reconciliation - Reconcile SmartBooks cash accounts with you financial institution. &nbsp;'),
(101, 104, 'd', 'en_us', '07.06.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/06-GenLedger/01-ChartOfAccounts/ChartHome.html', 'General Journal.Chart of Accounts', 'General Journal - Chart of Accounts', 'General Journal - Chart of Accounts\r \r \r \r \r General Journal - Chart of Accounts\r The chart of accounts is the key to a successful accounting application. Phreebooks allow for accounts name that include characters as well as numbers. It also allows for sub-accounts to be used later in roll-up reporting. If you are not sure how to set up your chart of accounts, refer to your accountant or use one of the supplied chart of accounts during the set-up script.\r Notes: \r \r   Exactly one account of type ''Retained Earnings'' may be part of the chart of accounts.\r   Accounts cannot be deleted if they have been used in a journal entry.\r   Accounts should be checked as inactive if they are no longer used but have past journal entries against it.\r \r Adding a general ledger account\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Chart of Accounts.\r   Click on the New icon and a popup will appear.\r   Enter the GL account number (0-9 and a-z are allowed).\r   Enter the description, and subaccount information as necessary.\r   Enter the Account Type. This classifies the account and how entries are treated in the general journal.\r   Press Save to create the account and close the window.\r \r Deleting a general ledger account\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Chart of Accounts.\r   Click the Delete icon next to the account to be deleted.\r   Acknowledge the deletion and the account will be removed.\r     NOTE: if the account has journal entries in the database, the account cannot be deleted.\r \r Editing a general ledger account\r \r   Select General Ledger-Chart of Accounts.\r   Click the edit icon next to the account to be edited. \r   Make any changes and press Save to commit your changes and close the window.\r     NOTE: Account numbers cannot be changed if they have a journal entry posted against it.\r \r Related Links\r General Journal Entries\r   Reports - Balance Sheet\r   Reports - Income Statement\r &nbsp;'),
(102, 104, 'd', 'en_us', '07.06.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/06-GenLedger/02-JournalEntries/JournalHome.html', 'General Journal.Journal Entries', 'General Journal - Journal Entries', 'General Journal - Journal Entries\r \r \r \r \r General Journal - Journal Entries\r Entries can be made directly into the general journal. However, most entries are handled in the background as through the system scripts.\r Notes:\r \r   The journal must be in balance before the entry can be posted.\r   The accounts selected must be a valid entry from the chart of accounts. \r \r Posting a general journal entry:\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Journal Entry.\r   Enter the general ledger account and a description of the entry. A popup window listing the chart of accounts. \r   Enter the amount of the journal entry.\r   Repeat steps 2-3 for all entries. Use the Add icon to add additional rows.\r   Verify the journal entries are in balance and press the Save icon to commit the changes.\r \r Editing a general journal entry: \r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Journal Entry.\r   Select the Open icon and a popup window will appear listing the entries for the current period. Select the entry to be edited or use the search/period selection to search for entries outside of the current period..\r   Edit any fields as necessary.\r   Verify the journal entries are in balance and press the Save icon to commit the changes. This action will first un-post the prior entry and re-post with the new values. \r \r Deleting a general journal entry:\r \r   Select General Journal-&gt;Journal Entry.\r   Select the Open icon and a popup window will appear listing the entries for the current period. Select the entry to be edited or use the search/period selection to search for entries outside of the current period..\r   Press the delete Icon and after confirmation, the journal entry will be un-posted and removed from the database.\r \r Related Links\r Chart of Accounts\r   Reports - Balance Sheet\r Reports - Income Statement \r &nbsp; \r &nbsp;'),
(103, 104, 'd', 'en_us', '07.06.03', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/06-GenLedger/03-Utilities/UtilitiesHome.html', 'General Journal.Utilities', 'General Journal - Utilities', 'General Journal - Utilities     General Journal - Utilities General Journal utilities provide administrative functions such as fiscal year setup, defining the current accounting period, setting up beginning balances and purging the database tables. Security should be restricted to the general journal utilities since significant damage to the company data can be had here.  General Journal Utilities include: Accounting period change - Sets the current accounting period to a specified period. typically, this will need to be changed at the start of each accounting period as defined in the fiscal year. Fiscal Year setup, addition and change - the first fiscal year is set up through the setup script. This script allows for changes to any fiscal year and also generates the next fiscal year.  NOTE: For performance reasons, it is best not to generate the next fiscal year until it is necessary. Every journal entry that affects the financial statement propagates through the remaining periods from the post date to the last period defined in the database. This results in extra queries to the database and slows down each posting. NOTE: Once an entry has been entered for a period, the fiscal year for that period and any earlier periods will be locked and cannot be deleted or changed. Beginning Balances - This utility assists in transferring information from other accounting systems into SmartBooks to retain continuity of financial reporting. Beginning balances set the trial balance accounts prior to period 1 (the default first accounting period). The beginning balance utility also allows for importing of inventory balances and valuation, customer accounts receivable, and vendor accounts payable. Database purge - THIS FUNCTION WILL DESTROY ALL THE JOURNAL ENTRIES AND BEGINNING BALANCES. It is included for test and evaluation purposes to quickly erase all journal entries and resets inventory balances to zero. It will not remove customers, vendors, employees or other set-up settings. &nbsp;'),
(104, 118, '0', 'en_us', '07.06', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/06-GenLedger/GLHome.html', 'General Ledger', 'General Ledger Home', 'General Ledger Home     General Ledger Home &nbsp;'),
(105, 115, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/01-Languages/LanguagesHome.html', 'Setup.Languages', 'Setup - Languages', 'Setup - Languages     Setup - Languages Phreebooks is designed for multi-language capability. The standard release includes translations for English (US). Language modules, as they come available, are available at the SmartBooks website. Prior to login, the directory /modules/general/language is read and all loaded language modules will appear in a drop down at login. Once a language is selected, it is stored in a session variable and will remain in effect unitl the user logs out.'),
(106, 115, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/02-Currencies/CurrenciesHome.html', 'Setup.Currencies', 'Setup - Currencies', 'Setup - Currencies     Setup - Currencies SmartBooks is designed to handle multiple currencies. the US Dollar is the default currency shipped with the standard release. Updating the exchange rate  Exchange rates can be updated through two exchange servers, oanda and xe. Oanda is the primary server and xe is the backup server should oanda be down.     Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the Update Exchange Rate icon, . The exchange rat servers will be queried and the rates updated.   Adding a Currency    Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the New icon and a popup will appear.   Select the Title of the currency, i.e. US Dollar, Euro, Yen, etc.    Enter the ISO code for the currency, USD, EUR, etc.    Enter the symbol to use to the left and/or right, $ for USD, &euro; for EUR, etc.    Enter the symbol to use for the thousands place and decimal places.   Enter the current exchange rate relative to the default currency. Leave the value blank if it will be updated when the exchange rate is updated.   If this is to be the default currency, check the Set as Default box.    Press the Save icon to save the entry into the database.   Press the Update Exchange Rate icon to refresh the current exchange rate with the exchange rate servers.   Changing the Default Currency    Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the Edit icon next to the currency to set as default and a popup will appear.   Check the Set as Default box.    Press the Save icon to save the entry into the database.  Deleteing a Currency    Select Setup-&gt;Currencies.   Press the Delete icon next to the currency to delete and a confirmation popup will appear.   Press OK to confirm the deletion and the currency will be removed from the database.   Related Links &nbsp;'),
(107, 109, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.03.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/03-SalesTax/01-TaxAuthorities.html', 'Setup.Sales Tax Authorities', 'Setup - Sales Tax Authorities', 'Setup - Sales Tax Authorities\r \r \r \r \r Setup - Sales Tax Authorities\r Sales tax authorities can be set for one or more Tax Authorities. they can be assigned a different collection account to help facilitate tracking and payment of taxes collected. Sales tax authorities need to be set up prior to setting up sales tax rates.\r Adding a Sales Tax Authority\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Authorities.\r   Press the New icon. A popup will appear with a form to fill out.\r   Enter a short name for the taxing authority, e.g. state tax, city tax, vat, etc.\r   Enter a more detailed description of the taxing authority.\r   Enter the general ledger account to track taxes collected for this authority.\r    If the vendor is in the database, select the vendor to use to send payment to when submitting the taxes to the authority.\r    Enter the tax rate in percent, e.g. 7.2, 15.0, etc. Use a decimal point (.) for non-integer percentages.\r   Press the Save icon to add the sales tax authority to the database.\r \r Editing a Sales Tax Authority\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Authorities.\r   Press the Edit icon next to the sales tax authority to edit. A popup will appear with a form pre-filled with the current data.\r   Make any necessary changes and press the Save icon to update the sales tax authority in the database.\r   \r Deleting a Sales Tax Authority\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Authorities.\r   Press the Delete icon next to the sales tax authority to Delete. A confirmation popup will appear.\r   Press OK to confirm the deletion and the sales tax authority will be removed from the  database.\r \r Related Links\r Sales Tax Overview\r   Sales Tax Rates \r Adding a Vendor Account\r   Adding a General Ledger Account'),
(108, 109, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.03.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/03-SalesTax/02-TaxRates.html', 'Setup.Sales Tax Rates', 'Setup - Sales Tax Rates', 'Setup - Sales Tax Rates\r \r \r \r \r Setup - Sales Tax Rates\r Sales tax rates can be set at several levels depending on the taxing structure of your business. Prior to setting up sales tax rates, sales tax authorities need to be set up. Refer the the help file on Sales Tax Authorities for more information.\r Adding a Sales Tax Rate\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Rates.\r   Press the New icon. A popup will appear with a form to fill out.\r   Enter a short name for the tax rate, e.g. Local Tax, State TAX, VAT, etc.\r   Enter a more detailed description of the tax rate.\r   To add or delete a taxing authority, select it from the appropriate list. NOTE: Only one authority can be added or removed at this time. To add more than one authority, save the entry and then edit it to add more. \r   If freight is taxable, selct the Yes radio box. \r   Press the Save icon to commit the entry to the database. \r \r Editing a Sales Tax Rate\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Rates.\r   Press the Edit icon next to the sales tax rate to edit. A popup will appear with a form filled out with the current tax rate information.\r   Edit the short name or description as necessary.\r   To add or delete a taxing authority, select it from the appropriate list. NOTE: Only one authority can be added or removed at this time. To add more than one authority, save the entry and then edit it to add or remove another authority. \r   If freight is taxable, selct the Yes radio box. \r   Press the Save icon to commit the change to the database.\r \r Deleting a Sales Tax Rate\r \r   Select Setup-&gt;Sales Tax Rates.\r   Press the Delete icon next to the sales tax rate to delete. A confirmation popup will appear to verfiy the delete request.\r   Press OK to remove the sales tax rate from the database.\r \r Related Links\r Sales Tax Overview\r   Sales Tax Authorities'),
(109, 115, '0', 'en_us', '07.08.03', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/03-SalesTax/SalesTaxHome.html', 'Setup.Sales Tax', 'Setup - Sales Tax', 'Setup - Sales Tax\r \r \r \r \r Setup - Sales Tax\r SmartBooks has a multilevel sales tax rate calculator built in. Sales tax is comprised of Tax Authorities and Tax Rates. Tax authorities are defined as the agencies that collect the tax and tax rates are a collection of one or more authorities. \r Phreebooks inventory items can be individually set as taxable or non-taxable. When an order is placed, one sales tax rate is applied to the entire order, but will not be calculated if the inventory item is tagged as non-taxable. For example, if a labor item is included in the invoice and is not taxable, it shouldbe flagged as non-taxable in the inventory database and thus will not be included in the sales tax calculation for the invoice. \r See the links below for detailed information on setting up, managing and removing sales tax authorities and rates. \r Related Links \r Sales Tax Authorities\r Sales Tax Rates'),
(110, 115, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.04', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/04-Branches/BranchesHome.html', 'Setup.Company Branches', 'Setup - Company Branches', 'Setup - Company Branches     Setup - Company Branches &nbsp;'),
(111, 113, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.06.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/06-ImportExport/01-ImportData.html', 'Setup.Importing Data', 'Importing Data', 'Importing Data\r \r \r \r \r Importing Data\r Data can be imported into SmartBooks such as customers, vendors, and inventory. \r The HOW TOs contain samples of import procedures to import customers, vendors, and inventory.\r Related Links\r Importing/Exporting Overview\r   Exporting Data from SmartBooks'),
(112, 113, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.06.02', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/06-ImportExport/02-ExportData.html', 'Setup.Exporting Data', 'Exporting Data', 'Exporting Data\r \r \r \r \r Exporting Data\r Data can be exported from SmartBooks to text files for use in other applications. \r The HOW TOs contain samples of export procedures to export customers, vendors, and inventory.\r Related Links\r Importing/Exporting Overview\r   Importing Data into SmartBooks'),
(113, 115, '0', 'en_us', '07.08.06', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/06-ImportExport/ImpExpHome.html', 'Setup.Importing Data', 'Importing/Exporting Data', 'Importing/Exporting Data\r \r \r \r \r Importing and Exporting Data\r SmartBooks has a powerful import/export tool to transfer data in to/out of the SmartBooks database. Knowledge of the SmartBooks database structure and data fields are necessary to acurately import information into the database. Exporting is less complicated but still required some knowledge of the database tables. \r Most import/export operations deal solely with a single database table. The exception is the account definitions (customers, vendors, branches). These definitions include the address book fields (currently set at 5) with the main account information.\r Other import scripts specialized towards beginning balance initialization can be found here.\r The HOW TOs contain samples of import procedures to import customers, vendors, and inventory.\r Related Links\r Importing Data into SmartBooks\r   Exporting Data from SmartBooks'),
(114, 115, 'd', 'en_us', '07.08.07', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/07-Users/UserHome.html', 'Setup.Users', 'Setup - Users', 'Setup - Users     Setup - Users SmartBooks user accounts allow for individualized access to the PhreBooks modules. User accounts are used in the audit log, setting access permissions, and permissions for reports.  When the SmartBooks systems is installed, a single administrator account is added given full permission to access all of the SmartBooks functionality. New users can be added and thier access can be controlled to modules that they are given permission to access. If No Access is given to a function, the option will not appear in their menu when they log in.  NOTE: When adding new modules, permissions have not been established and the modules will not be visible. Each user account will need to be edited and the appropriate permission added to access the module. Adding a User Account     Select Setup-&gt;Users.   Press the Add icon. A new screen will appear with a form to fill out for the new user.   Enter a username, email address, and password for the new user.   Set the permissions for the user. A tab will appear for each main heading. the permissions are initially set for no access for all modules. Select the permission levels for each module in each tab.   Press the Save icon to create the user account.  Editing a User Account    Select Setup-&gt;Users.   Press the Edit icon next to the user to edit. A new screen will appear with a form  fill out for the new user.   Edit any user information and security permissions as necesary. If the password will no be changed, leave the password fields blank and no changes will be made to the current password in the database.    Press the Save icon to update the user account.  Deleting a User Account    Select Setup-&gt;Users.   Press the Delete icon next to the user to delete. A popup will appear to confirm the selection.    Press OK to confirm the selection and the user account will be removed from the database.  Related Links &nbsp;'),
(115, 118, '0', 'en_us', '07.08', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/08-Setup/SetupHome.html', 'Setup', 'Setup Home', 'Setup Home     Setup Home Company setup modules allow for customization of SmartBooks to meet the needs of your business. Several modules are included with the standard release of SmartBooks but others may be available for download at www.SmartBooks.com. the standard modules include: Languages Currencies Sales Tax Countries States/Provinces Branches Shipping Payment Price Sheets ZenCart Interface User Maintenance &nbsp;'),
(116, 117, 'd', 'en_us', '07.09.01', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/09-Configuration/01-ControlPanel.html', 'Control Panel', 'Control Panel', 'Control Panel     Control Panel &nbsp;'),
(117, 118, '0', 'en_us', '07.09', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/09-Configuration/ConfigHome.html', 'Configuration', 'Configuration', 'Configuration     Configuration &nbsp;'),
(118, 0, '0', 'en_us', '07', 'modules/smartbooks/language/en_us/manual/UserManualHome.html', 'User Manual', 'User Manual', 'User Manual     SmartBooks Users Manual Please select a category to view: Vendors - Your suppliers of goods and services.  Customers - Those that receive you companies goods and services.  Inventory - The goods and services your company produces/sells. Banking - Your financial receivables (customer payments), payables ( customer payments) and activities related to your financial institution.  General Ledger - The accounting ledgers to track your companies overall performance. Employees - Your companies work force, sales reps, and other personnel used to operate your company.  Setup - Defines the modules activated, security settings, and other parameters needed to tailor SmartBooks to you company.  Configuration and Defaults - Sets the default information to use throughout SmartBooks. Defined default general ledger accounts, required information, and other initial settings used.'),
